    },
    {
      "identifier": "solText",
      "name": "Slice of Life",
      "role": "system",        
      "content": "{{setvar::style::Naturalism: write the ordinary with full attention. Small moments carry the scene. Nothing needs to be significant to be worth writing. Dialogue: characters talk around nothing in particular. Conversations drift, interrupt, and trail off. People talk past each other without malice. Rhythm: sentences are shorter and more varied than in dramatic scenes. Let the prose breathe. Observation: notice the peripheral detail. The thing happening in the background while the main characters speak. The habit, the texture, the small repeated gesture. Stakes: low or invisible. The tension is in the unspoken, not the dramatic. Resist the urge to escalate. Mood: unhurried. The scene does not need to arrive anywhere. Being in the moment is the point. }}{{trim}}",
      "system_prompt": true,
      "enabled": false,        
